title: For Sale/Trade:  Sig Sauer P226 **MUST SEE**
location: North Nashville; Hendersonville; Gallatin, Nashville, Tennessee
postcontent:
The item displayed in the images below is a Sig Sauer P226 that was manufactured in West Germany and issued to the German police force. As a certified Sig Armorer, I have taken this handgun completely down and cleaned every inch of this weapon. All worn springs, pins, and other components have been removed and replaced with new ones and the old worn exterior has been redone with a sleek yet extremely durable Cerakote finish. 

Having similar results to other competitors when it comes to impact testing, Cerakote really shines when it comes to corrosion resistance and wear resistance--meaning your weapon can handle whatever you throw at it. When properly applied, the Cerakote finish adds lubricity to the metal, allowing parts that come in contact with one another to glide past each other more easily.
See for yourself in the full report at this link: http://www.cerakoteguncoatings.com/resources/files/testing/fullTechnicalReport.pdf 

The following parts have been Cerakoted:
--The slide
--Guide rod
--Firing pin housing
--Extractor
--Frame
--Take down lever
--Trigger
--Trigger pivot pin
--Trigger bar
--Slide release lever
--Decocking lever
--Locking plate
--Ejector
--Sear
--Safety lever (internal safety mechanism)
--Magazine catch
--Magazine catch stop
--Hammer

I have personally tested this firearm to make sure everything is in working order and that all features function as they were intended to by the manufacturer. Since the chamber in any Sig Sauer pistol is manufactured to such tight tolerances, the barrel has been blued rather than cerakoted to ensure that function is not affected. I was careful to make sure that all the beautiful little import marks were left in tact and not covered up by the Cerakote. 

Another huge plus with this firearm is that it has the new style E2 grips from Sig that do not require any screws to hold them in place (I was skeptical about it too until I had some serious range time to test the product out--these grips are awesome). The E2 grips are actually more comfortable than the Hogue grips that came on my 226 Elite, as they are contoured to fit the shape of a human hand rather than just being flat on the sides. This pistol also comes with tritium night sights from Sig--which as you probably know, is an expensive upgrade in itself. 

Note in the pictures, on the right side of the trigger and hammer, there are small blemishes in the finish. They are purely cosmetic and will not affect the function of the firearm. You should be able to see the trigger blemish in the pictures below if you look very closely. The one on the hammer is very hard to notice. 

Shoot me an email if you have any questions about this item. I purchased it for my own personal collection but am selling it to fund another project. Since the item is used, it is being sold "as is," but I am confident you will love it for years to come. There are some small imperfections from where the pistol was carried in a holster, but nothing to be concerned about. Even though it is a simple process, due to a lack of time, the sights have not been zeroed yet. They are the proper sights for this particular pistol (it had a dead on combat zero prior to Cerakoting), they just need to be nudged back into the correct position.

Would prefer cash, but may consider the right trades. 
Please--no low ball offers--this is an extremely high quality product that has been gone through and tested by a certified armorer. Includes everything seen in the pictures.

In order to obtain your concealed handgun license (CHL) in Texas, you must take a class consisting of 4-6 hours of classroom instruction, a multiple choice exam, and a live fire demonstration. If the thought of sitting in a classroom for 4-6 hours of state mandated training reminds you of everything thatâs wrong with defensive driving classes, youâve come to the right place. Texas CHL classes from Hooten Armory are fun. The instructor is passionate about firearms, safety and proficiency. Our training philosophy is that if you are enjoying yourself, you will absorb more information, youâll retain it longer, and youâll be more willing to continue your education. As the saying goes, time really does fly when you are having fun.

The course begins in the classroom and covers four topics: Handgun Use, Safe and Proper Storage of Handguns and Ammunition, Non-Violent Dispute Resolution, and the legal Use of Force. title: For Sale:  Beretta 84.
location: West Raleigh, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I have a Beretta 84 chambered in .380 auto (9 short). This is not a "b", "bb", or "cheetah" model but the original 84. Date code of AC puts it made in 1977. The 84 is very much a miniature version of the Beretta 92 but chambered in .380 Auto. The gun is double/single action but no de-cocker was ever put into the original 84. The one mag it comes with is a double stack mag that holds 13 rounds plus one in the chamber. Because it is still a small framed auto it makes a fantastic .380 for carry. 

Being as the gun is nearly 40 years old, it obviously is not mint, but still in excellent condition. After I had bought this gun a while back, I completely detail stripped the firearm, cleaned and duracoated the frame matte black. The slide and all other steel parts were then re-blued. Additionally, all the old laquer that was originally used to coat the wood grips were removed, the nics and dings from the last 38 years sanded out, and then treated with several coats of hand rubbed raw, unprocessed linseed oil. This finish will slowly oxidize over the years gaining a rich red patina as it ages in the walnut. Essentially looking better and better with age. This little gun will no doubt gain value the older it gets and the harder it gets to find. 

$380

If you have any other questions about it, feel free to contact me through email or text/call Nine One Zero///7Five9///Nine44Two thanks for looking.

In development for more than four years, the VP9 is Heckler & Kochâs latest handgun and the first striker fired HK since the renowned P7 series pistols were introduced in the 1980s.  Experience gained by HK engineers with the recent P30 pistol had a direct influence on the design of the VP9, but the VP9 breaks new ground with its integration of a unique striker firing system with an enhanced HK âlight pullâ trigger. The net result is trigger quality unequaled in any production striker fired handgun. HK pioneered the first striker fired handguns, producing both the VP70 and P7 series, designs that impacted several models by HK competitors. But a superior trigger has eluded most striker fired pistol designs. The VP9 trigger surpasses those found on competitors. It has a short, light take-up with a solid, single action type break followed by a short positive reset. The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall/crisp break. Typically, striker fired guns have a pre-travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. With the VP9, you have a less than noticeable pre-travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break. The VP9 uses HKâs ergonomic handgun grip design that includes three changeable backstraps and six side panelsâ accommodating all hand sizes. Molded finger grooves in the front of the pistolâs grip also instinctively position an operatorâs hand for optimal shooting. Only HK handguns have such a customized grip. Although influenced by other HK models, the VP9 has all the hallmarks of the latest, state-of-the-art handgun. All controls are completely ambidextrous. Slide releases are present on both sides of the frame and the magazine release can be easily activated by left- or right-handed shooters. A new feature is HKâs patented charging supports â simple components that are mounted on each side of the rear of the slide and provide better gripping leverage for racking the slide rearward. The charging supports speed reloading and make operating the VP9 easier for shooters with reduced hand strength. The VP pistols uses the proven P30 steel magazine; 15 and 10-round capacity available. The VP9 has an extended Picatinny MIL-STD-1913 rail molded into its polymer frame for mounting lights and accessories. The rail has been tested and certified to handle mounted accessories up to 5.6 ounces. The VP9âs proprietary captive flat recoil spring helps reduce the recoil forces effecting the operator and the handgun, improving shooter control during rapid firing and prolonging component service life. HKâs famous cold hammer forged barrel â made from cannon grade steel â ensures long service life. Similar HK barrels on 9 mm P30 models have fired more than 90,000 rounds in endurance tests in 2010. The polygonal bore profile, with no traditional lands-and-grooves rifling, contributes to longer service life as well as a slight increase in muzzle velocity. The VP9âs machined steel slide is protected from corrosion and wear by HKâs hostile environment finish and all metal components, including springs and pins have superior metallurgy. VP pistols are made in Heckler & Kochâs Oberndorf factory in southwest Germany. The VP9 is well-suited for civilian sport shooting, security, military, and law enforcement use. Covered by Heckler & Kochâs limited lifetime warranty, the HK VP9 is a solid design engineered with the famous long-term durability that make HK products especially cost-effective when subjected to total life cycle cost analysis.
